#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""jig's verify script (story build-scripts, issue #14).

Independently re-runs a task's Done-means items — one PASS/FAIL per item,
never a single suite-level boolean — instead of trusting the executor's
claim that they're satisfied (docs/design/build-scripts.md, "Proposed
design"; PRODUCT.md's "Nothing signs off on itself" principle). Takes its
item list from exactly one of two sources:

- `--items <json>`: an already-extracted item list (a small JSON document
  — see the module-level `ITEMS_SCHEMA` note below), hand-transcribed by
  the orchestrating model from a `PLAN.md` task block.
- `--plan <path> --task <label>`: derives the items mechanically from the
  named task's checkpoint block — the same grammar `scripts/plan-lint`
  validates and `skills/build/SKILL.md` documents, parsed by the shared
  `scripts/_planparse.py` module so the two scripts can't drift apart.
  `--task` names the task by its heading number (`3` or `Task 3`).
  A `script`/`test-backed` item's backtick-quoted repo-relative method
  path becomes its `command` verbatim; that derivation is fully
  mechanical. A `probe` item's artifact/pattern isn't in the plan grammar
  at all, so it comes from the optional `--probe-spec <json>` supplement
  (see `PROBE_SPEC_SCHEMA` below) — a task whose block has probe items
  but no supplement entry for them is a usage error (exit 2) naming
  exactly which item ids need one; a task with no probe items needs no
  supplement. Everything downstream (checks, output, --out, --since,
  exit codes) behaves identically in both modes.

Each item names a verification tier (`script` | `test-backed` | `probe` —
DESIGN.md's closed enum; no `judgment` tier permitted):

- `script` / `test-backed`: runs the item's own named `command` via the
  shell and checks its exit code.
- `probe`: confirms a caller-supplied `artifact` file exists, is non-empty,
  and (if given) matches an expected `pattern` — verify never takes the
  screenshot or runs `ps` on the executor's behalf, since choosing what
  observation proves a capability is the checkpoint-block author's call,
  not a generic script's to invent.

Every item — `cap` and `hold` alike — must PASS for the overall result to
be PASS; per-item results are always reported, even on an overall PASS, so
a caller can tell whether a repeat failure lands on the *same* item as
before.

Fails closed rather than passing vacuously: an empty or malformed item list
is a usage error (exit 2), never a PASS (docs/studious/premortems/
build-scripts.md, risk #4). A `probe` item also needs `--since` — an
ISO-8601 timestamp or a git revision — so a stale artifact copied forward
from a prior attempt can't pass just because no `pattern` was supplied
(same premortem doc, risk #5); this recency floor is verify's own, not
merely delegated to the downstream `evidence-capture` freshness check.

Trust boundary (issue #48): each `script`/`test-backed` item's `command` is
plan-supplied (transcribed by `/build`'s Foreman from `PLAN.md`'s Done-means
prose) and is executed verbatim via the shell -- `shell=True`, no
allowlist, sandbox, or confirmation gate. Commands in a plan are executed
verbatim via the shell; only run /build on plans you would run by hand.

Timeout (issue #49): each command-tier item runs under `--timeout` seconds
(a generous default -- suites legitimately run minutes). A hung command
(waiting on stdin, deadlocked, a network-bound test with no timeout of its
own) is killed and reported as a distinct FAIL detail (`TIMEOUT: ...`),
never conflated with the item's own non-zero-exit FAIL detail (`exit
code: ...`) -- a hang produces no exit code at all, so the two cases must
read differently. A timed-out item still counts as FAIL toward the overall
result, same as any other failing item. The kill takes down the command's
whole process group, not just the shell (issue #61) -- via
`_gitutil.run_shell_with_timeout`, launched with `start_new_session=True`
and killed on timeout with `os.killpg(process.pid, signal.SIGKILL)` -- so a
backgrounded or piped child can't outlive the shell that was reported
killed.

Parallelism (opt-in): `--parallel` runs command-tier items concurrently in
a thread pool (each thread just waits on its own subprocess, so the GIL is
no constraint); the default stays exactly sequential. `probe` items are
cheap stat/regex checks and stay in-line on the main thread either way.
Results are printed in item order regardless of completion order -- the
report reads identically with or without the flag -- and per-item timeout
semantics are unchanged (each command still gets the full `--timeout`, and
a hang is still the same distinct `TIMEOUT: ...` FAIL detail).

ITEMS_SCHEMA (JSON):
    {
      "task": "task-1",
      "items": [
        {"id": 1, "kind": "cap", "tier": "script", "command": "ruff check x.py"},
        {"id": 2, "kind": "hold", "tier": "test-backed", "command": "python -m unittest tests.test_x.Case.test_y"},
        {"id": 3, "kind": "cap", "tier": "probe", "artifact": "path/to/evidence.txt", "pattern": "no orphaned process"}
      ]
    }

PROBE_SPEC_SCHEMA (JSON, `--probe-spec`, plan mode only): item id (the
block's own list number, as a string) -> the probe fields the plan grammar
doesn't carry. Only probe-tier items ever appear here; an entry naming a
non-probe or absent item id is a usage error (a transcription bug, not a
check to silently drop).
    {
      "3": {"artifact": "path/to/evidence.txt", "pattern": "no orphaned process"}
    }

Exit codes: 0 every item PASS. 1 at least one item FAIL. 2 usage error
(malformed/empty items, missing --since for a probe item, an unparseable
plan task or missing probe supplement in --plan mode).
"""
from __future__ import annotations

import argparse
import json
import re
import subprocess
import sys
from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor
from dataclasses import asdict, dataclass
from datetime import datetime
from pathlib import Path
from textwrap import indent

sys.path.insert(0, str(Path(__file__).resolve().parent))
from _gitutil import DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS, resolve_revision_epoch, run_shell_with_timeout  # noqa: E402
from _planparse import COMMAND_TIERS, TIER_BODY_RE, VALID_TIERS, Item, parse_items, split_tasks  # noqa: E402

VALID_KINDS = frozenset({"cap", "hold"})

# --task names a task by its heading number: a bare "3" or the "Task 3"
# label form, matching TASK_HEADING_RE's own capture. Never by title --
# titles need the ambiguity rules plan-lint's load-bearing derivation
# carries, and a mechanical transcription already knows the number.
TASK_LABEL_RE = re.compile(r"(?:task\s+)?(\d+)", re.IGNORECASE)


@dataclass
class ItemResult:
    id: object
    kind: str
    tier: str
    status: str  # PASS | FAIL
    detail: str


def load_items(path: Path) -> dict:
    """Load and validate the items document; raises ValueError on any problem."""
    try:
        data = json.loads(path.read_text(encoding="utf-8"))
    except OSError as exc:
        raise ValueError(f"could not read items file '{path}': {exc}") from exc
    except json.JSONDecodeError as exc:
        raise ValueError(f"items file '{path}' is not valid JSON: {exc}") from exc

    if not isinstance(data, dict) or "items" not in data:
        raise ValueError(f"items file '{path}' must be a JSON object with an 'items' list")

    items = data["items"]
    if not isinstance(items, list) or not items:
        raise ValueError("no items to verify: 'items' must be a non-empty list")

    for i, item in enumerate(items):
        label = f"item #{i}"
        if not isinstance(item, dict):
            raise ValueError(f"{label} is not a JSON object")
        if "id" not in item:
            raise ValueError(f"{label} is missing required field 'id'")
        label = f"item {item['id']!r}"

        kind = item.get("kind")
        if kind not in VALID_KINDS:
            raise ValueError(f"{label}: 'kind' must be one of {sorted(VALID_KINDS)}, got {kind!r}")

        tier = item.get("tier")
        if tier not in VALID_TIERS:
            raise ValueError(
                f"{label}: 'tier' must be one of {sorted(VALID_TIERS)}, got {tier!r} "
                "(no 'judgment' tier permitted)"
            )

        if tier in COMMAND_TIERS and not item.get("command"):
            raise ValueError(f"{label}: tier '{tier}' requires a non-empty 'command'")
        if tier == "probe" and not item.get("artifact"):
            raise ValueError(f"{label}: tier 'probe' requires a non-empty 'artifact' path")

    return data


def load_probe_spec(path: Path) -> dict[str, dict]:
    """Load and validate the --probe-spec supplement; raises ValueError on any problem."""
    try:
        data = json.loads(path.read_text(encoding="utf-8"))
    except OSError as exc:
        raise ValueError(f"could not read probe-spec file '{path}': {exc}") from exc
    except json.JSONDecodeError as exc:
        raise ValueError(f"probe-spec file '{path}' is not valid JSON: {exc}") from exc

    if not isinstance(data, dict):
        raise ValueError(f"probe-spec file '{path}' must be a JSON object mapping item id -> {{artifact, pattern}}")
    for key, entry in data.items():
        if not isinstance(entry, dict) or not entry.get("artifact"):
            raise ValueError(f"probe-spec entry {key!r} must be an object with a non-empty 'artifact' path")
    return data


def resolve_task_number(label: str) -> str:
    """Resolve --task to a task heading number: '3' or 'Task 3'."""
    m = TASK_LABEL_RE.fullmatch(label.strip())
    if m is None:
        raise ValueError(f"--task '{label}' names no task heading number (expected e.g. '3' or 'Task 3')")
    return m.group(1)


def parse_item_tier(item: Item) -> tuple[str, str | None]:
    """An item's (tier_word, method_path) per the checkpoint-block grammar;
    raises ValueError on anything the closed enum or shape rejects."""
    if item.tier_body is None:
        raise ValueError(f"item {item.num} has no '(tier: ...)' parenthetical")
    m = TIER_BODY_RE.match(item.tier_body.strip())
    if not m:
        raise ValueError(f"item {item.num} tier annotation is malformed: {item.tier_body!r}")
    tier_word, method_path = m.group(1), m.group(2)
    if tier_word not in VALID_TIERS:
        raise ValueError(
            f"item {item.num} tier '{tier_word}' is not one of {sorted(VALID_TIERS)} (no 'judgment' tier permitted)"
        )
    return tier_word, method_path


def derive_items_from_plan(plan_path: Path, task_label: str, probe_spec_path: Path | None) -> dict:
    """Build an ITEMS_SCHEMA document mechanically from `plan_path`'s named
    task block; raises ValueError (a usage error, exit 2) on any problem —
    fail closed, never a silently partial item list."""
    try:
        text = plan_path.read_text(encoding="utf-8")
    except OSError as exc:
        raise ValueError(f"could not read plan file '{plan_path}': {exc}") from exc

    tasks = split_tasks(text)
    if not tasks:
        raise ValueError(f"plan '{plan_path}' contains no '### Task' headings -- nothing to derive items from")

    task_num = resolve_task_number(task_label)
    blocks = [block for num, block in tasks if num == task_num]
    if not blocks:
        available = ", ".join(num for num, _ in tasks)
        raise ValueError(f"task {task_num} not found in '{plan_path}' (tasks present: {available})")
    if len(blocks) > 1:
        raise ValueError(f"task {task_num} appears {len(blocks)} times in '{plan_path}' -- ambiguous")

    parsed = parse_items(blocks[0])
    if not parsed:
        raise ValueError(f"task {task_num} in '{plan_path}' has no 'Done means' items -- nothing to verify")

    tiered = [(item, *parse_item_tier(item)) for item in parsed]
    for item, tier, method_path in tiered:
        if tier in COMMAND_TIERS and not method_path:
            raise ValueError(
                f"item {item.num} (tier: {tier}) names no backtick-quoted method path -- "
                "its command can't be derived mechanically"
            )

    probe_spec = load_probe_spec(probe_spec_path) if probe_spec_path else {}

    probe_nums = {item.num for item, tier, _ in tiered if tier == "probe"}
    unknown = sorted(set(probe_spec) - probe_nums)
    if unknown:
        raise ValueError(
            f"--probe-spec entr{'ies' if len(unknown) > 1 else 'y'} {', '.join(unknown)} "
            f"match no probe-tier item of task {task_num}"
        )
    missing = [item.num for item, tier, _ in tiered if tier == "probe" and item.num not in probe_spec]
    if missing:
        raise ValueError(
            f"probe-tier item(s) {', '.join(missing)} of task {task_num} need an artifact (and optional "
            "pattern) the plan grammar doesn't carry -- supply --probe-spec JSON mapping each listed "
            'item id to {"artifact": ..., "pattern": ...}'
        )

    def derive(item: Item, tier: str, method_path: str | None) -> dict:
        if tier in COMMAND_TIERS:
            return {"id": int(item.num), "kind": item.kind, "tier": tier, "command": method_path}
        entry = probe_spec[item.num]
        derived = {"id": int(item.num), "kind": item.kind, "tier": tier, "artifact": entry["artifact"]}
        if "pattern" in entry:
            derived["pattern"] = entry["pattern"]
        return derived

    return {"task": f"task-{task_num}", "items": [derive(*t) for t in tiered]}


def resolve_since(since: str, repo: Path) -> float:
    """Resolve --since to a POSIX epoch: an ISO-8601 timestamp or a git revision."""
    try:
        return datetime.fromisoformat(since.replace("Z", "+00:00")).timestamp()
    except ValueError:
        pass
    epoch = resolve_revision_epoch(repo, since)
    if epoch is None:
        raise ValueError(
            f"--since value '{since}' is neither an ISO-8601 timestamp nor a "
            "resolvable git revision"
        )
    return epoch


def check_command_item(item: dict, repo: Path, timeout: float) -> ItemResult:
    try:
        result = run_shell_with_timeout(item["command"], repo, timeout)
    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired as exc:
        detail = (
            f"command: {item['command']}\n"
            f"TIMEOUT: did not finish within --timeout {timeout:g}s and was killed -- "
            "distinct from an ordinary non-zero-exit failure detail below, since a hung "
            "command produces no exit status of its own (issue #49)\n"
            f"--- stdout captured before timeout ---\n{exc.stdout or ''}\n"
            f"--- stderr captured before timeout ---\n{exc.stderr or ''}"
        )
        return ItemResult(item["id"], item["kind"], item["tier"], "FAIL", detail)
    status = "PASS" if result.returncode == 0 else "FAIL"
    detail = (
        f"command: {item['command']}\n"
        f"exit code: {result.returncode}\n"
        f"--- stdout ---\n{result.stdout}\n--- stderr ---\n{result.stderr}"
    )
    return ItemResult(item["id"], item["kind"], item["tier"], status, detail)


def check_probe_item(item: dict, since_ts: float) -> ItemResult:
    artifact = Path(item["artifact"])
    if not artifact.is_file():
        return ItemResult(item["id"], item["kind"], item["tier"], "FAIL", f"artifact not found: {artifact}")
    if artifact.stat().st_size == 0:
        return ItemResult(item["id"], item["kind"], item["tier"], "FAIL", f"artifact is empty: {artifact}")
    if artifact.stat().st_mtime < since_ts:
        return ItemResult(
            item["id"], item["kind"], item["tier"], "FAIL",
            f"artifact is stale — its mtime predates --since: {artifact}",
        )
    pattern = item.get("pattern")
    if pattern and not re.search(pattern, artifact.read_text(encoding="utf-8", errors="replace")):
        return ItemResult(
            item["id"], item["kind"], item["tier"], "FAIL",
            f"artifact does not match expected pattern {pattern!r}: {artifact}",
        )
    return ItemResult(item["id"], item["kind"], item["tier"], "PASS", f"artifact ok: {artifact}")


def run_items(
    items: list[dict], repo: Path, timeout: float, since_ts: float | None, parallel: bool
) -> list[ItemResult]:
    """Check every item, returning results in item order.

    Sequential by default. With `parallel`, command-tier items run
    concurrently in a thread pool (one worker per command item -- each
    thread only waits on its own subprocess) while probe items, cheap stat
    checks, stay in-line on the main thread; collecting each future by its
    item's own position keeps the output order deterministic regardless of
    completion order.
    """
    if not parallel:
        return [
            check_probe_item(item, since_ts) if item["tier"] == "probe" else check_command_item(item, repo, timeout)
            for item in items
        ]

    command_indexes = [i for i, item in enumerate(items) if item["tier"] in COMMAND_TIERS]
    with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=max(1, len(command_indexes))) as pool:
        futures = {i: pool.submit(check_command_item, items[i], repo, timeout) for i in command_indexes}
        return [
            futures[i].result() if i in futures else check_probe_item(item, since_ts)
            for i, item in enumerate(items)
        ]


def parse_args(argv: list[str]) -> argparse.Namespace:
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(
        prog="verify",
        description="Independently re-run a task's Done-means items, one PASS/FAIL per item.",
    )
    source = parser.add_mutually_exclusive_group(required=True)
    source.add_argument("--items", help="path to the task's items JSON document")
    source.add_argument(
        "--plan",
        help="path to a PLAN.md-shaped file to derive the items from mechanically (requires --task)",
    )
    parser.add_argument(
        "--task",
        default=None,
        help="which of --plan's tasks to derive: its heading number, e.g. '3' or 'Task 3'",
    )
    parser.add_argument(
        "--probe-spec",
        default=None,
        help=(
            "path to a JSON object mapping a probe-tier item id to its "
            '{"artifact": ..., "pattern": ...} — the one hand-authored supplement '
            "--plan mode can need, since the plan grammar carries no artifact/pattern "
            "for a probe item (only with --plan)"
        ),
    )
    parser.add_argument(
        "--repo", default=".", help="working directory for 'command' tiers and for resolving --since as a git revision"
    )
    parser.add_argument(
        "--since",
        default=None,
        help="ISO-8601 timestamp or git revision a 'probe' artifact must not predate",
    )
    parser.add_argument(
        "--timeout",
        type=float,
        default=DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS,
        help=(
            "seconds to allow each 'script'/'test-backed' item's command to run "
            f"before treating it as hung and killing it (default: {DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS:g}s "
            "-- suites legitimately run minutes; issue #49)"
        ),
    )
    parser.add_argument(
        "--parallel",
        action="store_true",
        help=(
            "run 'script'/'test-backed' items concurrently (default: sequential); "
            "results still print in item order, and each item keeps its own full --timeout"
        ),
    )
    parser.add_argument("--out", default=None, help="path to write a JSON results document")
    args = parser.parse_args(argv)

    # argparse's own mutual-exclusion check covers --items vs --plan; these
    # cross-flag rules ride the same usage-error convention (exit 2).
    if args.plan and not args.task:
        parser.error("--plan requires --task (which task block to derive items from)")
    if args.task and not args.plan:
        parser.error("--task only makes sense with --plan")
    if args.probe_spec and not args.plan:
        parser.error("--probe-spec only makes sense with --plan")
    return args


def main(argv: list[str]) -> int:
    args = parse_args(argv)

    try:
        data = (
            derive_items_from_plan(Path(args.plan), args.task, Path(args.probe_spec) if args.probe_spec else None)
            if args.plan
            else load_items(Path(args.items))
        )
    except ValueError as exc:
        print(f"error: {exc}", file=sys.stderr)
        return 2

    items = data["items"]
    repo = Path(args.repo).resolve()
    has_probe = any(item["tier"] == "probe" for item in items)

    since_ts: float | None = None
    if args.since is not None:
        try:
            since_ts = resolve_since(args.since, repo)
        except ValueError as exc:
            print(f"error: {exc}", file=sys.stderr)
            return 2
    elif has_probe:
        print(
            "error: items include a 'probe'-tier check but no --since was given. "
            "A probe artifact needs a freshness floor (e.g. the task's start time "
            "or the worktree's baseline commit) or a stale artifact copied forward "
            "from a prior attempt would pass silently.",
            file=sys.stderr,
        )
        return 2

    results = run_items(items, repo, args.timeout, since_ts, args.parallel)

    for r in results:
        print(f"[{r.status}] item {r.id} ({r.kind}/{r.tier})")
        if r.status == "FAIL":
            print(indent(r.detail, "    "))

    passed = sum(r.status == "PASS" for r in results)
    overall = "PASS" if passed == len(results) else "FAIL"
    print(f"verify: task={data.get('task', '?')} overall={overall} ({passed}/{len(results)} items pass)")

    if args.out:
        Path(args.out).write_text(
            json.dumps(
                {"task": data.get("task"), "overall": overall, "items": [asdict(r) for r in results]},
                indent=2,
            ),
            encoding="utf-8",
        )

    return 0 if overall == "PASS" else 1


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main(sys.argv[1:]))
